com.inqwell.any.server.cache

Class CacheMap

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.inqwell.any.AbstractComposite
      • com.inqwell.any.AbstractMap
        • com.inqwell.any.PropertyAccessMap
          • com.inqwell.any.AnyMap
            • com.inqwell.any.server.cache.CacheMap
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Any, Composite, Map, Cache, Serializable, Cloneable

    public final class CacheMap
extends AnyMap
implements Cache
    The CacheMap class is a Map whose values are kept as normal (i.e. strong) references.

    Cloning is not supported. The mutating methods add() and remove(), and the access method get() are synchronized. This ensures thread-safety.

    By default the other methods of the CacheMap class are not synchronized. Instances may be wrapped in a com.inqwell.any.SynchronizedMap object to effect thread safety overall but things like entries() are generally not important enough to warrant the overhead of synchronization and cannot be relied on either.

    A Cache can accept single or multi-valued entries. If multi-valued then the items added to the cache must be objects implementing com.inqwell.any.Array. The CacheMap class creates its own array objects. Thus the client is free to mutate its original array without affecting the CacheMap. The contents of a Cache instance must be homogenous - it is illegal to mix single and multi-valued entries.

    A multi-valued cache entry will be removed when all of the values held against the key are removed. This is distinct from deleting the value from the set, for which the new method remove (key, value) is provided. This method preserves the cache entry if there are still items in the multi-value set.

      • remove

        public void remove(Any key,
                   Any value)
        Remove a (potentially) multi-valued element from the cache. This is a Cache specific removal method which accepts a value as well as a key. If the key maps to anything other than an array the entry is removed. If the map value is an array then the item in the array comparing for equality with the given value is removed and the cache entry is kept.

        Note that the array should not hold duplicates as only a single item is removed from it.

        Specified by:
        remove in interface Cache

      • add

        public void add(Any key,
                Any value)
        Adds value to the cache against key. The semantics of add are somewhat different for caches than other Map implementations:
        • If the cache is single valued the an exception is thrown for duplicate keys. This is the same as for normal maps.
        • If the cache is multi-valued and the key is already present the value being added must not be an array or an exception is thrown. The value will be added to the existing multi-value entry.
        • If the cache is multi-valued and the key is not present the value being added must be an array. Otherwise the add operation is ignored.

        Specified by:
        add in interface Map
        Overrides:
        add in class AnyMap

      • uniqueReference

        public Any uniqueReference(Any key,
                           Any value)
        Query the cache and add the object if not present returning what was given. This method is only supported if the cache is operating in single-value mode. If an entry is present then that entry is returned. Otherwise the object is added and returned. This allows a particular cache to act as a reference list for all the objects within it.
        Specified by:
        uniqueReference in interface Cache
